  "type": "fault_tree",
  "exportedAt": "2026-07-14T09:00:00.000Z",
  "description": "The same emergency cooling system as the RBD example, read backwards: what has to fail for there to be no cooling flow when it is called for. The top event is an OR of four ways to lose flow — both trains fail (an AND over the two per-train ORs, which is where the redundancy lives), the shared suction header blocks, station power is lost, or the 2-out-of-3 start logic fails to command the pumps (a K/N gate, k=2 of 3 sensors). Note the notation: a gate feeds an intermediate event, and that event feeds the next gate. Gates never wire straight into other gates. Top-event probability is 0.0059, from 9 minimal cut sets: 2 of order 1 (suction header, station power) and 7 of order 2 (four two-train combinations, three sensor pairs). The lesson is in the importance measures. Station power has a probability of just 0.004 — a fifth of the 0.02 pump failure — yet it carries a Fussell-Vesely of 0.68 against the pump's 0.08, because power is a single point of failure while pumps only matter in pairs. Redundancy is worth nothing against the things it does not cover. Run minimal cut sets, then importance measures.",
